name: 4-chloroanisole
Reason: To predict the melting point of 4-chloroanisole, we will start with the basic structure of benzene and consider the effects of the methoxy (-OCH3) and chloro (-Cl) substituents on the benzene ring. Benzene has a melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius. The presence of a methoxy group generally increases the melting point due to an increase in polarity and potential for hydrogen bonding; however, in this case, there is no hydrogen bonding because there are no hydrogens on the oxygen. Nevertheless, the -OCH3 group is an electron-donating group which slightly increases the dipole moment and thus can increase the melting point. We can estimate an increase of about +20 degrees Celsius for the methoxy group. The chloro group is electron-withdrawing and slightly increases the rigidity of the structure which can lead to higher melting points; however, it also makes the molecule more polar. Let's estimate about a +10 degrees Celsius increase for the chloro group. Adding these increments to benzene's base melting point gives us a predicted melting point for 4-chloroanisole.
